{
  "doc_id": "7667",
  "text": "The use of poor-quality antimalarials can have a negative financial impact on patients and their families [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . Replacement or additional drugs, repeated courses of poor-quality antimalarials, repeated consultations at health facilities, and lost work days can all impose an unwanted economic burden [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] , Indeed, recent modeling assuming current incidence rates of malaria indicates that widespread artemisinin resistance can be expected to lead to 116,000 excess deaths annually [CITATION_7] . This burden may be particularly severe in some developing countries, where the majority of the population has to pay for their medicines and the cost of the medication represents a substantial proportion of the household income [CITATION_8] .",
